I want a small web app which persists and displays pieces of text. For the
moment I want to focus on the user interfaces. This app will have three
different interfaces:
- a CLI with which you can interact directly with the instance when logged in
  the same server
- an API with which you can interact remotely (eg through curl)
- an user friendly react app
We will implement this using typescript.

These three interfaces will share code. To begin with, we will have one
    interface Entry {
        text: string;
        createdAt: Date;
    }
We need the following structure:
    - src/cli  -> will contain the CLI specific code
    - src/web-ui  -> will contain all the react app code
    - src/web-api -> will contain the web-api code
    - src/domain  -> will contain things like the model I described above

The react app will be very simple. For the moment it should two routes:
 - /  -> the home of the app; simply contains a paragraph explaining this is a
   paste bin clone
 - /entries/{id}  -> will display one single entry. For this it will perform a
   GET /api/entries/{id} on startup
Note that this is an SPA, so we need react routing here

The WEB-API will have one single endpoint GET /api/entries/{id} which will serve the
entry of the given ID

But we will also have a CLI. The CLI will be called like this
    `paste-bin-clone get entry {id}`

Both the CLI and the WEB-API will request hardcoded data for the moment, but
they will request it from the same place.
Besides the four directories I mentioned above, we should have a fifth one:
    - src/core
There, at src/core/entries.ts we will have the following

    import { Entry } from "@domain/entry"

    class Entries {
        getByID(id: string): Entry | null {
            return {
                text: "foo, hardcoded entry"
            }
        }
    }


Note that I used "@domain" in the import. This is because we need that alias in
our typescript config. Besides, we need a "@core" alias. More concretely, we
eslint we should enforce the following:
 - We have "@domain" alias which refers to "src/domain"
 - We have "@core" alias which refers to "src/core"
 - We need to prohibit back imports (eg import { ... } from "../web-ui")
 - We need to make it such that
    - from src/web-ui we can only import "@domain"
    - from src/web-api we can import both “@domain" and “@core"
    - from src/cli we can import both “@domain" and “@core"
    - from src/core we can import only “@domain"

